• For your architecture, the DMA plan should select the RTAC resources, not all
  the relay resources, if the RTACs are already collecting the relay events/SOE.

  The relays still matter, but mainly as child/identity resources so DMA can
  label the records under the correct relay instead of only under the parent
  RTAC.

  Recommended Setup

  1. In Resource Management, each RTAC should have a resource with a POSTGRESQL
     connection:
      - Host: RTAC IP
      - Port: 5432
      - Database: 3530
      - Valid RTAC database credentials
  2. Each relay should exist as a resource only if you want DMA Archive/
     reporting to associate records to the relay.
     For that to work, each relay resource needs a globalDeviceId matching the
     RTAC-side relay Device GUID.
  3. On each RTAC POSTGRESQL connection, add the relay resources as Child
     Resources. The manual says child resources on a POSTGRESQL parent
     connection must have globalDeviceId configured.
  4. In Disturbance Monitoring > New Plan, create collection plans against the
     30 RTAC resources:
      - One plan for Oscillography/Event records if collecting CEV/COMTRADE.
      - One plan for SOE if the UI only lets you choose one report type per
        plan.
      - Same 30 RTACs can be used in both plans.
  5. In the plan’s advanced options, pay attention to the misconfigured GUID
     policy:
      - Default shown in the manual: Associate with Parent Resource
      - That means if a relay GUID does not match a child resource, DMA will
        file the data under the RTAC.

  RTAC Side
  Use the RTAC DMA Link extension if possible. It sets up the pieces DMA
  expects:

  - RTAC GUID
  - SEL Client Device GUIDs for relays
  - Event collection type: CEV or COMTRADE
  - ASCII SER logging for SOE
  - DMA_Listening_SEL
  - New Event Notification = Encrypted Database
  - Unsolicited Event/SOE notices to Blueframe

  For 30 RTACs, I would use Listening if allowed by the network. RTAC sends
  notification to Blueframe on TCP 5000; DMA then connects back to the RTAC
  database on 5432 and collects new reports. Polling still works, but listening
  avoids hammering all RTACs on a schedule.

  Bottom Line
  Select the RTACs in the DMA plan. Keep the relays as child resources with
  matching GUIDs if you want the archive to show “Relay X event” instead of
  “RTAC Y event.” If you select both RTACs and relays for direct collection, you
  risk duplicate or split collection unless that is intentional.







For your DMA setup, use Blueframe DMA email publishing, not RTAC Email Plus,
  unless you specifically want each RTAC to send its own emails.

  Blueframe DMA Email Setup

  1. Create the SMTP resource
      - Go to Resource Management
      - Add/configure an SMTP or SMTPS resource
      - Set server address, port, TLS/authentication, credentials as required by
        your mail server
  2. Create the target email group
      - Open Notifications
      - Go to Recipient Groups
      - Select New Recipient Group
      - Pick the SMTP server resource
      - Set the sender/from address
      - Add the target email addresses
      - Create/save the group
  3. Create the DMA email publisher
      - Open Disturbance Monitoring
      - Go to Publishing
      - Select New Publisher
      - Set:
          - Type: Email
          - Recipient Group: your target email group
          - Report Type: SOE or Oscillography, depending what you want emailed
      - Select resources:
          - If records are associated to relay child resources, select the relay
            resources
          - If records show under parent RTACs, select the RTAC resources
      - Create the publisher
  4. Make sure collection/listening is already working
     Emails are sent when new data is collected into DMA. If you create the
     email publisher after old events were already collected, it generally won’t
     email those old records.

  RTAC Email Plus Alternative
  If you mean the RTAC’s Email Plus extension:

  - Insert Email Plus
  - Set Emailer Type to Monitored Events
  - Configure SMTP server, port, TLS, username/password, sender
  - On Recipient Groups, add the target email addresses
  - On Monitored Events, add each SEL Protocol client/relay, assign a recipient
    group, and choose attachment type: None, CEV, or COMTRADE
  - Use Auto-Config Device = True to enable new-event filtering and required
    event tags

  For your 30-RTAC DMA architecture, I’d centralize it in Blueframe Publishing
  unless there is a requirement for station-local RTAC emails.
